tip.text: Fantastic buildings with beautiful interiors, and the free daily tour was fascinating.
There sure is some good coffee around the little towns of the South Island. Loved this nice, strong coffee from Gusto. Was the perfect pick me up after another night at sea.
The architecture of the railway station in Dunedin is beautiful, with stained windows, monogrammed tiles and even a small museum upstairs.
Baldwin Street, an homage to the largest acting family in the world. Not really, but it is the steepest street in the world, with a wonderful view at the top.
Lovely little coastal town. You can get some decent coffee on High St, but also stop by the bakery on Auckland and try some green lip mussels and wine while you're here.
This huge playground is pretty kickass - with slides, rock-climbing, flying fox, climbing tower, sandpits, rope climbing, water play areas and more.
The new climbing structure with the slide at the top is a definite hit with the kids.
The danishes at this little bakery in Clayton are so good, I don't know why I haven't been sooner. That custard is fantastic!
Grab a drink or a bite to eat at sunset and enjoy that view.
Only really impressive views if you are staying here. Not worth the stop if you are passing by.
The scallop mornay pie is a winner - full of fresh, sweet scallops
Cozy little coffee shop, tucked away at the rear of the building, but follow the artwork from the street. A great range of breakfast jaffles too.

formattedAddress: Shop 11 540 Little Collins St (Cnr Gallaghers Pl & Victoria La)

tip.text: The home of Mimi the Muttaburrasaurus - a 3m tall by 6m wide dinosaur playground activity with a ropes course, rock-climbing holds and a dinosaur egg-shaped cubby with eggshell seats.
Traditional and authentic gozleme, borek and pides. Delicious.
Great value lunch deals, got half a porchetta fugazza and pumpkin soup for just $10. Delicious too.
A hidden gem just a few suburbs away from Springvale, but great pho and bun bo hue (and easier parking!)
Some great ramen by the guys at Shyun down the road.
Double ramen noodles available at no extra cost.
Good coffee and one of the most banging counters ever. Love the fit out of this place.
This gem is hidden in plain sight. Old skool restaurant with some wicked buns (baos). Try the golden sands salted duck egg custard bun.
Definitely an experience to try, dessert art creations made in front of you.
Quick dumplings from Mama and what she does best. Great pan fried dumplings here.
Another iconic Melbourne coffee place with chairs on the ceiling. Quite a sight to see.
The xiao long bao are good here, but my favourite is the Shanghai fried rice cakes (shepherds purse for without the dark sauce).

location.address: Store 323, Level 3, Emporium Melbourne, 287 Lonsdale Street
formattedAddress: Store 323, Level 3, Emporium Melbourne, 287 Lonsdale Street (Swanston & Elizabeth Street)

tip.text: You won't get your food before you can get your wallet out to pay, but still one of the fastest places to get served. Ever.
The cutest little kids meals come in an plane tray.

venue.name: Sun With Moon Japanese Dining & Café

tip.text: Famous for their wanton noodles, and super spicy chilli, and their chilli was super spicy!
One of the few places to get Sarawak laksa in Melbourne.
Tried the Ayam Penyet and it was good, but goddamned that sambal chilli at the back was hot!
One of the few places in Melbourne that serves tsukemen ramen (dipping ramen).
A great view of Uluwatu temple along the cliff face. Kecak dance from about 5/6pm. Also careful of the monkeys that like to steal hats and glasses.
Nice atmosphere, great live music, and really enjoyed the Bali ribs and salad.
Authentic Indonesian food, but from Sunda (West Java), not Bali. We really enjoyed the gurame goreng (fried fish) and the hot fish soup.
A great range of ice creams, with fruit / creamy / premium flavours. They also deliver!
One of the oldest warungs in Bali, with traditional Balinese dance at about 8pm. The menu includes Balinese dishes (we tried the nasi babi guling & nasi bebek betutu) which were good.
Wonderful views of Kintamani volcano and Mount Batur (one of four volcanoes in Bali), but about 2.5+ hr drive from Seminyak. Break up the trip with a stop at the Tegallalang Rice Terraces on the way.
A nice beach with plenty of seafood restaurants to pick from for a sunset dinner. Most of them are a bit touristy and pricey, so check Foursquare reviews first.
Fantastic place for lunch. If you can, choose an outdoor gazebo with a view of the rice paddy fields. House specialty is the crispy duck.

formattedAddress: Jalan Raya Goa Gajah (Banjar Teges Peliatan - Ubud)

tip.text: More of a local place than filled with tourists, good for ayam betutu and sate.
Rock formations out at sea, Tanah Lot is about 40mins north of Seminyak. Best times to visit are around sunrise or sunset.
Ancient Balinese temple dating back to the 9th century. Don't bother buying a sarong from the markets, as they are free when you enter the grounds.
Beautiful waterfall about 500m walk from the car park. Not sure if you can swim, but nice to dip your feet and wade in on a hot day.
You can enjoy views of the Rice Paddy Terraces at Cafe Dewi (just past the main strip) without being bothered by street vendors.

Past the strip (when coming from Ubud), great place for a drink/bite with views of the rice paddy terraces, without the hassle of street vendors. But If you photo the farmer, expect to be asked for $.
Kintamani is a village on the western edge of the caldera and a great place to see Kintamani Volcano and Mount Batur (one of four volcanoes in Bali).
Rock formations out at sea, Tanah Lot is quite a tourist attraction, about 40mins north of Seminyak. Best times to visit are around sunrise or sunset.

venue.name: Tanah Lot Temple (Pura Luhur Tanah Lot)

tip.text: If you see the fried chicken burger on the specials menu, you know what to do.
Make sure you ask for the secret burger menu. You won't regret it.
Some really good burgers here. This is the Berlin, with kransky and sauerkraut.
With the warmer weather, the rice noodle bowls are perfect! Refreshing and delicious.
Tried the pork belly, lamb, prawn and battered fish tacos, and they were all fresh and delicious. Overall really impressed that they also all had different flavours.
A great kids area at the back of the library with a fantastic selection of books.
Great for a $10 burger special on Fridays.
Protip: Milleandb 20 layer crepe cakes stocked Wednesday  - Friday.
That chirashi!
Be sure to ask what the ramen lab special for the day is. Pictured dark ramen with crab wontons.
Some of the prettiest tarts you'll ever have!
Not just great for desserts, the savoury brunch options are worth having too! Sticky rice with lup cheong and mushroom pictured.
Some of the best burgers in Melbourne. The Atomic (pictured) comes with a kransky inside. Can also vouch for the Francis Underwoood and Jiro burgers.
A great range of sweets. There are even nut-free, gluten-free and egg-free options for those with allergies.
They do some great coffee, and the baked eggs with meatballs was equally good.
Warning: the really f**kin' hot chicken is really f**kin' hot.
#protip: if you can't handle the spicy chili food, neutralise it with soy milk.
The duck ramen was pretty damn good. Definitely worth a try.
Tiny little Japanese place with a great selection of bento boxes.
A small, intimate little Japanese place with fantastic tempura.
Skipped breakfast? Grab a breakfast brioche. They may look small, but they are surprisingly filling. Just right.
Great place for a run or walk around the lake in the morning. Also keep you eye out for a kangaroo or two.
Get the chili crab and naan bread to soak up all that saucey goodness.
Fantastic views, and that infinity pool in the SkyPark!
The Nespresso machine in each of the rooms is a really nice touch. #coffee
The Nespresso machine in each of the rooms is a really nice touch. #coffee
The kakuni pork is fantastic. So soft, and melts in your mouth.
One of the iconic landmarks in HK, if not for anything else, for the Bruce Lee statue.
It's all about N09
Great Indonesian food, and you can buy a jar of sambal chili for home too!
The place to go for quail. Best to book and also pre-order your spicy quails.
Must try: one of their signature dishes - baked pineapple tart charsiu bao.
Oh em gee. Roast pork roll. Do yourself a favour and grab one. :)
The Classic Joe had so much flavour in the meat, it really stood out. Fantastic! Still so sad that they closed. :(
I must say, the Francis Underwood burger at the Dandenong Pavilion was pretty damn brilliant. Flavoursome beef patty. Brioche bun but not soggy at all. Knife and fork: optional.
The burger at Little Chloe. Yum! And that pomegranate salad. Wow!
In my heyday I would do the kilo burger challenge. Oh well, this will have to suffice.
The burgers are fantastic but while you're here, pick up some herb chips too!
Mary Burger: American style burger was ok. Not too messy to eat and good flavours
The burgers are pretty good here. Follow them on twitter for the occasion special deal: @perkupburgers
The corn fritters are great, but so is this burger!
Southern Fried Chicken Burger at the National. Pretty damn good!
Overheard some of the staff say the pizza at Mantra Ray Cafe was good, so we checked it for dinner. The chili explosion pizza was great! Decent amount of kick, but not scratch your face off hot.
All you can eat yumcha is great,  but be sure to leave some room for dessert. Chocolate dumplings anyone?
The banh mi are the freshest you can get. Everything made inhouse and bread rolls baked every hour.

tip.text: Korean fried chicken and beer - what more could you want?
